A hap-harlot is a small coverlet made from rougher materials than that fine full sized bed coverlets of the 19th century.  Hap-harlots usually were made of hemp or linen warp and a rough, course wool for the weft.  Often woven in the typical coverlet 4 shaft over shot or double weave patterns. One weaver of note is William Rose of Rhode Island (died 1913) who is responsible for saving many of the colonial era drafts handed around between weavers in the New England area. He started one of the first guild, which died out after his death, but not before many of his drafts were shared with the weavers in the guild, thus saving many of them from obscurity.